{"key":"processedPost-13170759","value":{"id":13170759,"first":13170037,"last":13170759,"when":1284063620,"utime":"09/09/10 11:20 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>coirlover said:</b><br />I am pasteurizing the coir by adding boiling water to a 5 gallon bucket, cover with tin foil and let sit for an hour.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />That is not pasteurization in any way, shape or form.&nbsp; It's a half-assed attempt at sterilization and will lead to a higher rate of contamination if anything but coir is in the substrate.<br /><br />If you want the boost that coffee grinds will give, first make a pot of coffee and drink it.&nbsp; Take the <i>spent grinds</i> and add them to your moistened coir along with gypsum, and vermiculite if desired.&nbsp; After bringing the mix to field capacity as shown in the casing and/or manure video above, put the ingredients into a jar or bag and slowly heat it in water until the interior of the bag reaches 140F/60C and hold it there for 60 to 90 minutes. Don't let it exceed 160F/70C during this time. This part is also shown in that video.<br />RR","title":"Re: Coir and Coffee ground question regarding pasteurization","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}